segments.text: This is January 25, sitting in the beautiful living room out at Pebble Creek with Glenn Johnson.
Now, Glenn, check your mic.
Okay, I'll check my mic and see if it's working okay.
Glenn, for the sake of someone in years from now who might be listening to this or reading the transcript, would you summarize your
experience and background, where'd you grow up, go to school, and particularly your experience academically before you began to think about moving to College Station, Texas.
Sure.
Well, I was born in Cleveland, Ohio, 1930.
My mother and father were divorced when I was a baby, and so we moved to
little community called Sebring, Ohio, about 65 miles southeast of Cleveland.
And I spent my elementary and secondary years there in Sebring, at Sebring McKinley High School.
I attended undergraduate school at Kent State University, 1949 to 1953.
I had one year of teaching experience in a suburb of Cleveland, Euclid on Lake Erie.
I had two years of military duty because I'd been in the ROTC, so I went into the military and fulfilled that obligation, the two-year obligation.
When I came out of the service, it was in the middle of the summer,
So I knew I would be going back to Euclid, Ohio, and I used that summer to start my master's program at Ohio State University where I finished a master of arts with a thesis.
Later I became what was called a master teacher in Euclid, Ohio, then an assistant principal, and by that time I'd finished the master's and started my doctorate
at Columbia University going summers.
I was offered principal ships in Euclid and in a suburb of St. Louis, Missouri called Clayton, Missouri.
And I opted for the principal ship in Clayton, Missouri and spent three years there going to Columbia University for six-week summer terms.
And finally, my major professor said, it's time you must come into residence.
So I did.
I went into residence in 1966 through that academic year, 66, 67.
At the end of my residence, near the end of my residence, I was being interviewed for assistant superintendencies in upstate New York and a superintendency in a suburb of Chicago, Illinois.
And I got this phone call out of the clear blue sky, knew nothing about it coming, from a Dr. Paul Hanseling at Texas A&M University.
And he said that they had a new position for an assistant professor and that I seemed to have the credentials for that position.
And I asked him how he knew me, how he got these credentials.

and he said he had written to Columbia University and said this is what we're looking for and they sent me your credentials and we like what we see we'll pay to have you come down here for a couple of days and meet us and get acquainted with us and see if you would be interested so I talked to Ida I hadn't the foggiest idea where Texas A&M University was
I'd heard of it primarily because of football more than anything else.
I couldn't in my own mind while I was talking to Dr. Hentschling sort out if this was Texas Tech or Texas A&M or West Texas or East Texas or whatever.
There were so many to people who had never been to Texas and I had never been to Texas.
So I told Ida as we talked, you know, I've never been to Texas.
This is an opportunity for me to at least go visit Texas, and I'll continue looking at these other jobs.
So sure enough, I came down and really had not the inkling, no inkling at all, that I would end up staying here.
But I liked what I saw.
I thought it was a nice community.
I had four very young children.
This looked like a nice place after living in places like St. Louis, Missouri and New York City.
They have four young children grow up.
And I guess the key factor was when I finished my presentation to the faculty in the Department of Education in the College of Liberal Arts.
And I finished interviewing with the key people, Bill Graves and Paul Hanserling.

and they took me up to meet the dean of the college who was Frank W.R. Hubert and Frank Hubert painted for me what Texas A&M University is today and I had I had no idea as I looked at what I saw in 1967
What we see today is, you know, it's just beyond your comprehension, and yet Frank Hubert saw this.
And he was very strong in his support of President Earl Rudder.
I believe I interviewed with, from there I think I interviewed with Byers, Vice President Byers, I believe.
And my final stop, which really came as a total shock,
because I never dreamed I'd go beyond the college dean.
But there I was.
I'd been with the vice president.
Now they were taking me over to meet the president of this university, Earl Rudder.
That just was beyond my comprehension.
And Earl Rudder was a very gentle man.
He was very courteous.
He said he had heard good things about me.
Hope that I like Texas A&M University.
And so when that interview was over, I signaled to Paul Hensling and Bill Graves that I'd like a couple of days to go home and think about this.
And they agreed to that.
When I got home, I described the situation to my wife, Ida.

and ask her if she thought we should go back and let her look at it she said no whatever i decided to do was going to be fine with her so i called paul and told him i would come and i've never regretted that move as far as you know
They were not contrasting you with anyone else.
They were looking at you, yes or no.
To my knowledge, that's true.
This 1967 spring, fall, what?
Spring.
Spring of 67.
Hoping for you to be here that fall.
That fall.
That's correct.
What was the, and we're not going to talk money any other time, what was the beginning salary?
Well, it was $12,400.
For 12 months or not?
That was for 12 months.
That was one of their selling points, by the way.

a lot of colleges and universities hire you only for nine months and then if they have the money they might negotiate either half summer or a full summer but Dr. Henseling made it clear and it was reinforced by Frank W.R. Hubert that what they were trying to do was to get people here 12 months so they were offering 12-month contracts
Try to summarize for this preservation what description they gave you of the aspirations they had for education.
Again, it was really Frank W.R. Hubert who painted this picture for me.
He said he thought in the not too distant future that they would have a college of education at Texas A&M University.
At the present time, at that time, they had just the Department of Education within the College of Liberal Arts.
But he said that I believe their projected enrollment for the fall was going to be somewhere around 600 ladies coming in to the programs at Texas A&M.
which proved to be true.
And that he saw nothing but tremendous growth because they had opened up recently to ladies coming into Texas A&M University.
And with the demand for the growing number of children and the demand for more schools, public schools and so forth, he saw that growth taking Texas A&M to eventually a college of education.

okay describe finding a place to live getting family here while I was here visiting Bill Graves did take me on a tour of the community and I guess the most startling thing that I saw was there just wasn't any restaurants to speak of I think we ate maybe at Tom's barbecue

and there was an A&W root beer and they took me out to the Briarcrest Country Club for a meal and that's where they said that's pretty much it if you wanted a nice meal you usually went to Briarcrest Country Club they said the Texan had just opened up on
What is that, South Main?
South Texas.
South College.
South College, yeah.
On South College.
And that didn't look too appetizing.
That was an old, run-down, drive-in hamburger place, I guess, before the new owners bought it and changed it to this really fine restaurant.
We were surprised the first time we ate there.
They really turned out good food.
But several times, I know when we did move here several times, we'd go out to Caldwell to eat.
We'd go out to the Surrey Inn out there to eat because there just weren't many choices here.
Right.
As you were looking for housing, what did you find?
I didn't find anything off the bat, but I lucked out again because...

One of the professors in the College of Liberal Arts in the Department of English, Cannon, Dr. Cannon, said that he was into the rental business and he had a home that people had rented were going to be moving.
And he said, you know, he'd be more than happy if I wanted to rent that house.
And that's what we did.
We rented that house sight unseen.
We rented that home and lived there the first two years we were here.
Now, I said we weren't going to talk money again.
What was that first rent?
I have no idea.
I don't recall what it was.
I'll bet it was a little bit less than the cost in either St. Louis, Cleveland, or New York City.
Oh, yes.
In fact, that was another factor that came into play.
You know, the beginning salary was not comparable to what people were talking about for assistant superintendent up in New York or superintendent of the suburb of Chicago.
There was no comparison.
But when you calculated in, factored in the cost of living, you could do pretty well.
It wasn't still going to match a superintendent's job, but still.
Right.
Describe the faculty in education when you came.
Who were the key veterans and the important newcomers and so forth?
Well, the key person at that time, of course, was Dr. Paul Hansling, who was head of the department in
My recollection was that he had somewhere along the line established a relationship with Frank W.R. Hubert out in the public school sector because Dr. Hubert had also been out at Orange, as I recall.
and had risen to the status of a superintendent there before going to the Texas Education Agency.
Now, I may have that reversed.
He may have...
Both.
Both?
He was my seventh grade band director.
Then he goes away to the Army, comes back, is the principal in Orange, then goes to Austin with the Texas Education Agency, also completes his doctoral degree
goes back to Orange as superintendent, and then comes here in 59 as the dean of arts and sciences before that was broken up.
Now, one of the things that I'm pretty sure it was Frank W.R. Hubert that told me this.
I feel fairly confident, but he's still alive, so you could check with Frank on this.
But I believe at one time I may have asked him, you know, how did he end up at Texas A&M University?
And he said he had this relationship with, I believe it was Edgars, who was commissioner, or...
Yes.
Is that right?
Commissioner of Education?
He had preceded, he was the superintendent in Orange.
during World War II and then went to Austin as the superintendent of the Austin system and then moved up.
And he knew Hubert well.
Would you like coffee or tea, hot cider?
Hot cider a little later, whenever he's going to have some.
That was J.W.?
J.W.
Edgar.
And the way I heard the story was that Earl Rudder
when he decided that he wanted education to move at Texas A&M University and that he too had foreseen somewhere down the line a college of education.
He had an opening for the Dean of Liberal Arts or may have been called Arts and Sciences.
Arts and Sciences, yes.
And he wanted to know who was the best educator in Texas that he could go after.
and maybe convinced to come to Texas A&M.
And the person he talked to was J.W.
Edgars, Commissioner of Education.
And the story I heard was that J.W.
Edgars didn't hesitate.
He said, that's Frank W.R. Hubert.
And so he went after Hubert, and the rest is history.
Okay, but who were the other key people?
Okay, after Paul, within the department,
To me it would have been Bill Graves, who was head of elementary education at that time.
And Bill wanted to move more into concentrating on the graduate programs in elementary education.
I forget who was in charge of secondary education at the time.
But he would have been Bill Graves' counterpart at the secondary level.
And he too wanted to get out of handling everything from undergraduate to graduate and concentrate more on the graduate programs.
So both of those gentlemen were going to concentrate on bringing in new people
who could take over the undergraduate program so it would free them up to concentrate on graduate programs.
And that's pretty much what happened.
Now, there were some reading people.
Don Barker was there.
He had an educational psychology background.
don't recall, I'd have to get an old catalog out and kind of review who the

key people were what was your describe your first assignments what were your courses and what did you see as your responsibilities well i had five courses that i had to teach and total responsibility for everything involving the elementary education program and my counterpart who came in at the same time had a secondary education background
And he assumed total responsibility for the undergraduate secondary program.
And both of us had... Who was that?
Again, you know, I really need a catalog to pull that out.
Jerry Salick.
Jerry Salick.
Jerry left after a couple of years and went on to other things, but...
Jerry and I kind of hit it off because we were both coming in new, and we had come out of programs where they were kind of on cutting-edge things.
For example, when I came down for my interview and talked to the faculty, made my presentation, it was on the use of development of non-graded technology.
schools and the use of what was called Flanders interaction analysis, a technique to measure the verbal interaction between teachers and students in classrooms.
And the faculty really was pretty oblivious to this.
They really weren't up on this.
They'd heard about it.
They may have read some articles in magazines, but they didn't understand

the details of it well jerry came out of that same kind of background and we immediately uh... started to talk about working together even though i was elementary with elementary prospective teachers and he was secondary with secondary prospective teachers we said you know maybe we can pool our resources
and combine a lot of our programs and really benefit from each other.
and the faculty that would be surrounding us.
And that's true.
That's true.
That's what happened.
With the blessing of Paul Hensling and Bill Graves and the person in charge of secondary, they thought that was a good concept.
And they liked what was called a block program.
They didn't know about block programs.
And they wanted us to implement a block program.
And we listened to them and said, yeah, we can do that.
So there were so few students at the undergraduate level

high enough status you know where they would be seniors i think i doubt if we had more than 30 elementary and secondary students all together that would reach that level and we could pull them into a block program and offer them all 15 hours together and so we just combined them we put the elementary and secondary and jerry had some things that the elementary
benefited from and he was delighted to have me train him in Flanders interaction analysis.
They knew nothing about that.
I think we only broke out for a course in elementary education, and he only broke out for a course in secondary education.
Otherwise, the history and philosophy of education, the teaching patterns and so forth, we combined and ran those as one class block program.
You mentioned a while ago responsibility for five courses to begin with.
How many per semester were you teaching?
I taught all five.
You taught five?
Five three-hour courses?
Five three-hour courses.
And at first, were there any graduate degrees available in education?
Yes.
There was a master's?
There was a master's degree.
Industrial Education, I believe it was, had their EDD, Doctor of Education.
I think that was...
But the enrollment was primarily undergraduate at the time you arrived.
Well, actually, they had a pretty good graduate enrollment.
It exceeded the...

undergraduate enrollment as I recall I could be off on that but if not it was awfully close and I think it was because historically people went elsewhere for undergraduate degrees in education and then came to Texas A&M
for their graduate degrees in either the Department of Education or Ag Education or Industrial Education.
And Ag Education and the College of Ag and Industrial Ed and Engineering would come over to the Department of Education to get student teaching and a couple other courses, as I recall.
As you began your work here,
Where was education located physically?
We were in the academic building and primarily on the top floor of the fourth floor of the old academic building.
Any stories about your first office or getting moved in?
Yes.
Probably the funniest thing that happened to me was
hiring people to work within the program.
And while we were still housed in the academic building, one of the people that I hired was an experienced kindergarten teacher.
Her name was Mary Bassett.
And she had been teaching kindergarten out at the Presbyterian Church.
And Mary came on board with us.
And I can recall probably the very first year that the College of Education had been formed,

we had a and i'd become a department head we had a meeting in in the room that we used on the fourth floor of the academic building and all of those rooms had all the windows had been nailed closed there there wasn't a window you could open and as i recall the story was because
They had air conditioning now and they didn't want people opening those windows so they simply nailed the darn things.
And it was really hot this one day that I was having a faculty meeting and as we were

uh... going along in the faculty meeting and everyone was hot and we could hardly wait to get out of there we continued to talk and proceed with the faculty meeting and mary bassett just very quietly got up walked over to the windows and took her shoe off and broke the window she'd had enough of that hot
room that I guess the air conditioner had gone out.
Now, you ask how my office was.
We shared offices then.
There were always about two of us to an office.
So I was sharing one of the small offices up there.
Right, now you were certainly well qualified by experience in the real world of education and Hubert was.
Hengeling, by and large was the departmental faculty all blessed with real education experience?
I'd say so.
Yeah, I'd say they had all been real practitioners out in the field.
As you chatted with these people before you came down here, did they talk about doctoral work in the future?
Were they hoping for doctoral programs in education?
No, I think it was too early.
I don't think the foresight that Frank Hubert had, and I assume in retrospect that was probably ongoing in the interaction with President Rutter,
So they would have had information that the faculty would not have had as they were trying to grease the tracks to get a college of education established, which came very quickly.
I mean, the end of my first year, I hadn't established myself statewide.
I'd been over in
met J.W.
Edgars.
I was back to make a presentation to the teacher education group there and won approval for the first kindergarten endorsement in the state of Texas, which threw everyone for a loop because
They did not associate Texas A&M with being innovative and bringing in new educational programs.
Nobody had a kindergarten endorsement in the state.
But I made a presentation that Frank Hubert said went extremely well because he was there and Edgars liked it.
And we just seemed to get almost immediate approval on implementing this new program.
Those kinds of interactions, and Frank Hubert was kind of leading me along.
He took me to various meetings throughout the state.
So in the spring of my very first year here, University of Texas came calling.
And I asked Dean Hubert if it would be all right if I went over.
They wanted to interview me for a position.
And his words to me were, yes, but don't you commit yourself until you come back here and talk to me.
And I said, fine.
They wined and dined, my wife and I, for two days over there at Forty Acres.
And before I left over there, they offered me a position as assistant professor.
My load would not be five courses, it would be one course.
I would not have all these student teachers to be responsible for.
I would have six graduate interns that I would work with.
They said that would probably be
my load each fall and each spring.
So, wow.
I came back and talked to Ida, and I said, I'm going over there.
Boy, that is really some deal.
And they offered me a salary increase, but I kept my word to Frank Hubert and went in and talked to him and told him I really couldn't turn that down.
That was so remarkable.
And that's when he said, well, listen, now this is not well known, but we're going to have a college of education, and I really want you to stay and be on the ground floor to form a foundation.
I see you as one of my department heads in this new college of education, and we'll match their salary.
And he said,
You can count on me to let you decide what your load's going to be because if my prediction is right, you'll have the authority to do that.
Wow.
And you'd been out of graduate school one year.
One year.
Pretty interesting year.
It was.
It was unbelievable.
Now that growth pattern at Texas A&M was just unparalleled, I think, in the history of maybe education period.
Because in retrospect, I think Rutter probably got that college of education established faster than anyone had ever gotten a college of education established.
We had, as I recall, 600 ladies that first year I came here.
It doubled the second year.
I think it was 1,200.
And it doubled again the third year.
It was like 2,400.
So there, Rutter and Hubert's crystal ball gazing was coming true.
They saw that kind of a massive growth taking place at A&M.
Describe...
You said you were with Hubert a few times when he made presentations to various groups.
Describe his technique.
